			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Yet Another Language Extension Scheme</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AnyaHeleneBagge.html">Anya Helene Bagge</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_9">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_9</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The paper proposes a scheme for extending languages, i.e., modular changes and integration with a host language.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> Language extension is fundamentally a language-design choice about new constructs and their interactions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagL">T1E: Reuse</span></a><ul><li> An extension scheme is also about reusing and re-combining existing language definitions.
</li></ul></li></ul>
